{"cursor":"7648","size":14,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n'Scientific evidence' is evidence which serves to either support or counter a\nscientific theory or hypothesis. Such evidence is expected to be empirical\nevidence and in accordance with scientific method. Standards for scientific\nevidence vary according to the field of inquiry, but the strength of scientific\nevidence is generally based on the results of statistical analysis and the\nstrength of scientific controls.\n","linknr":304,"url":"Scientific_evidence","recorded":1362676869,"links":19,"instances":["law"],"pdf":["http://www.fjc.gov/public/pdf.nsf/lookup/sciman00.pdf/$file/sciman00.pdf"],"categories":["Scientific method","Sources of knowledge","Evidence"],"headings":["Principles of inference","Utility of scientific evidence","Philosophic versus scientific views of scientific evidence","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f4/Ambox_content.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["scientific_evidence","law"]],"members":["scientific_evidence"],"related":["Evidence","Science","Scientific_theory","Hypothesis","Empirical_evidence","Scientific_method","Statistics","Scientific_control","Joseph_Priestley","Phlogiston_theory","Mercuric_oxide","Antoine_Lavoisier","Bayesian_inference","Prior_probability","Bayes'_theorem","Aumann's_agreement_theorem","Deductive_reasoning","Syllogism","Karl_R._Popper","Scientific_method","Philosophy_of_Science_Association","William_Bechtel","Peter_Achinstein","Carl_Hempel","Nelson_Goodman","R._B._Braithwaite","Norwood_Russell_Hanson","Wesley_C._Salmon","Rudolf_Carnap","Occam's_Razor","Anecdotal_evidence","Scientific_evidence_(law)","Science","Scientific_method"]}